1	Deep Learning Spectral Disentangling: Beyond Template Matching	deep-learning-spectral-disentangling-beyond-template-matching	ai	Binary star spectra adalah superposisi 2+ spektrum yang Doppler-shifted. Metode tradisional (KOREL, FDBinary) bekerja di 1D, tapi banyak informasi hilang saat ekstraksi dari 2D ke 1D.	1. Develop a novel deep learning framework for spectral disentangling that operates directly on 2D spectral images, bypassing traditional 1D extraction and template-fitting limitations.\r\n\r\n2. Achieve single-epoch component separation for double-lined spectroscopic binaries (SB2) using convolutional neural networks trained on synthetic binary spectra.\r\n\r\n3. Demonstrate superior performance over traditional methods (KOREL, FDBinary) especially for:\r\n   - Low SNR observations\r\n   - Heavily blended spectral lines  \r\n   - Unequal flux ratio systems (faint companions)\r\n   - Rapid rotators with broadened lines\r\n\r\n4. Create an automated pipeline for large-scale binary detection and characterization from ongoing spectroscopic surveys (APOGEE, LAMOST, GALAH, Gaia-RVS).\r\n\r\n5. Provide interpretable results through attention mechanisms that highlight which spectral features contribute to the disentangling process.	1. DATA PREPARATION\r\n   - Generate 100,000+ synthetic binary spectra using PHOENIX/MARCS stellar atmosphere models\r\n   - Combine spectra with varying: mass ratios (q=0.1-1.0), Doppler shifts (-300 to +300 km/s), \r\n     v sin i (0-200 km/s), flux ratios, and SNR (10-200)\r\n   - Augment with real observed binaries from APOGEE DR17 and LAMOST DR8\r\n   - Preserve 2D spectral format (echelle orders or long-slit)\r\n\r\n2. NEURAL NETWORK ARCHITECTURE\r\n   - Modified U-Net with dual decoders for component separation\r\n   - Input: 2D spectral image (orders × wavelength pixels)\r\n   - Encoder: Progressive feature extraction with spectral-aware convolutions\r\n   - Dual decoder branches: Component A and Component B spectra\r\n   - Physics-informed loss function: Lrecon + λ·Lphysics\r\n     where Lrecon ensures SpecA + SpecB = Observed\r\n     and Lphysics enforces stellar atmosphere constraints\r\n\r\n3. TRAINING STRATEGY\r\n   - Self-supervised pre-training on single stars with artificial combining\r\n   - Transfer learning from single to binary star domain\r\n   - Curriculum learning: simple (well-separated) to complex (heavily blended) cases\r\n   - Cross-validation with real binary systems with known orbital solutions\r\n\r\n4. VALIDATION & BENCHMARKING\r\n   - Compare with KOREL/FDBinary on standard binary benchmarks\r\n   - Test on eclipsing binaries with known parameters from TESS/Kepler\r\n   - Blind testing on newly observed HARPS/UVES spectra\r\n   - Quantitative metrics: spectral reconstruction error, parameter recovery accuracy\r\n\r\n5. INTERPRETABILITY\r\n   - Attention map visualization to identify critical spectral regions\r\n   - Gradient-based feature attribution\r\n   - Ablation studies on network components\r\n```	1. PRIMARY HYPOTHESIS: \r\n   Deep learning models operating directly on 2D spectral images can achieve more accurate spectral disentangling than traditional 1D template-based methods by preserving spatial-spectral correlations and learning complex non-linear mappings from blended to separated spectra.\r\n\r\n2. SECONDARY HYPOTHESES:\r\n   a) The 2D approach will be particularly advantageous for:\r\n      - Detecting faint companions (flux ratio < 0.1) invisible in 1D spectra\r\n      - Resolving heavily blended lines in rapid rotators\r\n      - Handling asymmetric line profiles from stellar activity/pulsations\r\n   \r\n   b) Self-supervised pre-training on synthetic binaries will enable successful \r\n      transfer to real observations despite domain shift between models and reality\r\n   \r\n   c) Attention mechanisms will reveal that the network primarily focuses on:\r\n      - Line core regions for radial velocity information\r\n      - Line wing shapes for v sin i determination  \r\n      - Relative line depths for flux ratio estimation\r\n\r\n3. EXPECTED OUTCOMES:\r\n   - 20-30% improvement in companion detection rate for faint secondaries\r\n   - 2-3× improvement in processing speed vs iterative methods\r\n   - Successful disentangling from single-epoch observations for well-separated systems\r\n   - Discovery of previously undetected binary companions in archival data\r\n\r\n4. NULL HYPOTHESIS:\r\n   The deep learning approach will show no significant improvement over traditional methods, suggesting that physics-based template fitting captures all recoverable information from the spectra.	2025-11-01	2026-02-28	planning	high	0				{}				f	f	2025-10-25 02:57:19.099674+00	2025-10-25 02:57:19.099692+00	2
